GoodNet — Licensing
====================

The platform consists of the kernel and the SDK. They live under a split
license model so that the kernel stays free in the strong sense while the
SDK — the boundary plugin authors compile against — remains permissive.
Plugins are independent builds and carry their own licenses; each plugin
directory has its own LICENSE file.


Platform Components
-------------------

  Kernel  (core/)                    GNU General Public License v2.0 (GPL-2.0)
                                     →  core/LICENSE

  SDK     (sdk/, public headers)     MIT License
                                     →  sdk/LICENSE


Plugins
-------

Plugins are independent builds. Each is licensed at the discretion of its
authors. Two distribution modes exist:

  - Dynamic plugins load through the stable C ABI at runtime. The boundary
    is the SDK (MIT), not GPL kernel internals. Such plugins may carry any
    license — MIT, BSD, Apache 2.0, proprietary — without triggering the
    kernel's copyleft.

  - Static plugins (currently: plugins/protocols/gnet, the mandatory
    mesh-framing protocol) are compiled into the kernel binary. Their
    source must be GPL-compatible — MIT and BSD qualify; Apache 2.0 is
    NOT compatible with GPL-2.0 and must not be used here.

In-tree convention for bundled plugins:

  - Reference / template / debug providers
    (null, raw, ...)               .. MIT License
  - Common transports
    (tcp, udp)                     .. MIT License
  - Mandatory mesh framing
    (gnet, statically linked)      .. MIT License (GPL-compatible)
  - Real implementations with
    original work and no obvious
    upstream analogues
    (noise, ipc, heartbeat, ...)   .. Apache 2.0 License

These are conventions for the bundled tree. Out-of-tree plugins choose
freely within the constraints above.

To discover the license of a specific plugin, consult its own LICENSE file.


